580@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“One day he remarked, without lifting his head, ‘In the interior you will no
581@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@doubt meet Mr. Kurtz.’ On my asking who Mr. Kurtz was, he said he was a
582@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@first-class agent; and seeing my disappointment at this information, he added
583@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@slowly, laying down his pen, ‘He is a very remarkable person.’ Further questions
584@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@elicited from him that Mr. Kurtz was at present in charge of a trading-post, a
585@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@very important one, in the true ivory-country, at ‘the very bottom of there.
586@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@Sends in as much ivory as all the others put together...’ He began to write
587@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@again. The sick man was too ill to groan.  The flies buzzed in a great peace.
588@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“Suddenly there was a growing murmur of voices and a great tramping of feet. A
589@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@caravan had come in. A violent babble of uncouth sounds burst out on the other
590@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@side of the planks. All the carriers were speaking together, and in the midst of
591@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@the uproar the lamentable voice of the chief agent was heard ‘giving it up’
592@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@tearfully for the twentieth time that day.... He rose slowly. ‘What a frightful
593@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@row,’ he said. He crossed the room gently to look at the sick man, and
594@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@returning, said to me, ‘He does not hear.’ ‘What!  Dead?’ I asked, startled.
595@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@‘No, not yet,’ he answered, with great composure.  Then, alluding with a toss of
596@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@the head to the tumult in the station-yard, ‘When one has got to make correct
597@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@entries, one comes to hate those savages—hate them to the death.’ He remained
598@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@thoughtful for a moment. ‘When you see Mr. Kurtz’ he went on, ‘tell him from me
599@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@that everything here’—he glanced at the deck—’ is very satisfactory. I don’t
600@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@like to write to him—with those messengers of ours you never know who may get
601@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@hold of your letter—at that Central Station.’ He stared at me for a moment with
602@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@his mild, bulging eyes. ‘Oh, he will go far, very far,’ he began again. ‘He will
603@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@be a somebody in the Administration before long. They, above—the Council in
604@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@Europe, you know—mean him to be.’
605@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“He turned to his work. The noise outside had ceased, and presently in going out
606@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@I stopped at the door. In the steady buzz of flies the homeward-bound agent was
607@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@lying finished and insensible; the other, bent over his books, was making
608@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@correct entries of perfectly correct transactions; and fifty feet below the
609@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@doorstep I could see the still tree-tops of the grove of death.
610@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“Next day I left that station at last, with a caravan of sixty men, for a
611@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@two-hundred-mile tramp.
612@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“No use telling you much about that. Paths, paths, everywhere; a stamped-in
613@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@network of paths spreading over the empty land, through the long grass, through
614@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@burnt grass, through thickets, down and up chilly ravines, up and down stony
615@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@hills ablaze with heat; and a solitude, a solitude, nobody, not a hut. The
616@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@population had cleared out a long time ago. Well, if a lot of mysterious niggers
617@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@armed with all kinds of fearful weapons suddenly took to travelling on the road
618@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@between Deal and Gravesend, catching the yokels right and left to carry heavy
619@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@loads for them, I fancy every farm and cottage thereabouts would get empty very
620@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@soon. Only here the dwellings were gone, too. Still I passed through several
621@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@abandoned villages. There’s something pathetically childish in the ruins of
622@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@grass walls. Day after day, with the stamp and shuffle of sixty pair of bare
623@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@feet behind me, each pair under a 60-lb. load. Camp, cook, sleep, strike camp,
624@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@march. Now and then a carrier dead in harness, at rest in the long grass near
625@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@the path, with an empty water-gourd and his long staff lying by his side. A
626@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@great silence around and above. Perhaps on some quiet night the tremor of
627@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@far-off drums, sinking, swelling, a tremor vast, faint; a sound weird,
628@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@appealing, suggestive, and wild—and perhaps with as profound a meaning as the
629@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@sound of bells in a Christian country. Once a white man in an unbuttoned
630@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@uniform, camping on the path with an armed escort of lank Zanzibaris, very
631@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@hospitable and festive—not to say drunk. Was looking after the upkeep of the
632@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@road, he declared. Can’t say I saw any road or any upkeep, unless the body of a
633@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@middle-aged negro, with a bullet-hole in the forehead, upon which I absolutely
634@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@stumbled three miles farther on, may be considered as a permanent improvement. I
635@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@had a white companion, too, not a bad chap, but rather too fleshy and with the
636@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@exasperating habit of fainting on the hot hillsides, miles away from the least
637@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@bit of shade and water. Annoying, you know, to hold your own coat like a parasol
638@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@over a man’s head while he is coming to. I couldn’t help asking him once what he
639@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@meant by coming there at all. ‘To make money, of course. What do you think?’ he
640@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@said, scornfully.  Then he got fever, and had to be carried in a hammock slung
641@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@under a pole.  As he weighed sixteen stone I had no end of rows with the
642@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@carriers. They jibbed, ran away, sneaked off with their loads in the night—quite
643@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@a mutiny.  So, one evening, I made a speech in English with gestures, not one of
644@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@which was lost to the sixty pairs of eyes before me, and the next morning I
645@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@started the hammock off in front all right. An hour afterwards I came upon the
646@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@whole concern wrecked in a bush—man, hammock, groans, blankets, horrors. The
647@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@heavy pole had skinned his poor nose. He was very anxious for me to kill
648@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@somebody, but there wasn’t the shadow of a carrier near.  I remembered the old
649@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@doctor—‘It would be interesting for science to watch the mental changes of
650@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@individuals, on the spot.’ I felt I was becoming scientifically interesting.
651@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@However, all that is to no purpose. On the fifteenth day I came in sight of the
652@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@big river again, and hobbled into the Central Station. It was on a back water
653@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@surrounded by scrub and forest, with a pretty border of smelly mud on one side,
654@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@and on the three others enclosed by a crazy fence of rushes. A neglected gap was
655@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@all the gate it had, and the first glance at the place was enough to let you see
656@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@the flabby devil was running that show. White men with long staves in their
657@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@hands appeared languidly from amongst the buildings, strolling up to take a look
658@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@at me, and then retired out of sight somewhere. One of them, a stout, excitable
659@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@chap with black moustaches, informed me with great volubility and many
660@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@digressions, as soon as I told him who I was, that my steamer was at the bottom
661@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@of the river. I was thunderstruck. What, how, why? Oh, it was ‘all right.’ The
662@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@‘manager himself’ was there. All quite correct. ‘Everybody had behaved
663@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@splendidly! splendidly!’—‘you must,’ he said in agitation, ‘go and see the
664@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@general manager at once. He is waiting!’
665@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“I did not see the real significance of that wreck at once. I fancy I see it
666@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@now, but I am not sure—not at all. Certainly the affair was too stupid—when I
667@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@think of it—to be altogether natural. Still... But at the moment it presented
668@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@itself simply as a confounded nuisance. The steamer was sunk. They had started
669@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@two days before in a sudden hurry up the river with the manager on board, in
670@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@charge of some volunteer skipper, and before they had been out three hours they
671@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@tore the bottom out of her on stones, and she sank near the south bank. I asked
672@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@myself what I was to do there, now my boat was lost. As a matter of fact, I had
673@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@plenty to do in fishing my command out of the river. I had to set about it the
674@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@very next day. That, and the repairs when I brought the pieces to the station,
675@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@took some months.
676@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“My first interview with the manager was curious. He did not ask me to sit down
677@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@after my twenty-mile walk that morning. He was commonplace in complexion, in
678@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@features, in manners, and in voice. He was of middle size and of ordinary build.
679@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@His eyes, of the usual blue, were perhaps remarkably cold, and he certainly
680@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@could make his glance fall on one as trenchant and heavy as an axe. But even at
681@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@these times the rest of his person seemed to disclaim the intention. Otherwise
682@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@there was only an indefinable, faint expression of his lips, something
683@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@stealthy—a smile—not a smile—I remember it, but I can’t explain. It was
684@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@unconscious, this smile was, though just after he had said something it got
685@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@intensified for an instant. It came at the end of his speeches like a seal
686@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@applied on the words to make the meaning of the commonest phrase appear
687@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@absolutely inscrutable. He was a common trader, from his youth up employed in
688@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@these parts—nothing more. He was obeyed, yet he inspired neither love nor fear,
689@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@nor even respect. He inspired uneasiness. That was it! Uneasiness. Not a
690@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@definite mistrust—just uneasiness—nothing more. You have no idea how effective
691@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@such a... a...  faculty can be. He had no genius for organizing, for initiative,
692@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@or for order even. That was evident in such things as the deplorable state of
693@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@the station. He had no learning, and no intelligence. His position had come to
694@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@him—why? Perhaps because he was never ill... He had served three terms of three
695@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@years out there... Because triumphant health in the general rout of
696@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@constitutions is a kind of power in itself. When he went home on leave he rioted
697@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@on a large scale—pompously. Jack ashore—with a difference—in externals only.
698@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@This one could gather from his casual talk. He originated nothing, he could keep
699@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@the routine going—that’s all. But he was great. He was great by this little
700@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@thing that it was impossible to tell what could control such a man. He never
701@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@gave that secret away. Perhaps there was nothing within him. Such a suspicion
702@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@made one pause—for out there there were no external checks. Once when various
703@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@tropical diseases had laid low almost every ‘agent’ in the station, he was heard
704@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@to say, ‘Men who come out here should have no entrails.’ He sealed the utterance
705@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@with that smile of his, as though it had been a door opening into a darkness he
706@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@had in his keeping. You fancied you had seen things—but the seal was on. When
707@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@annoyed at meal-times by the constant quarrels of the white men about
708@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@precedence, he ordered an immense round table to be made, for which a special
709@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@house had to be built. This was the station’s mess-room. Where he sat was the
710@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@first place—the rest were nowhere. One felt this to be his unalterable
711@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@conviction. He was neither civil nor uncivil. He was quiet. He allowed his
712@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@‘boy’—an overfed young negro from the coast—to treat the white men, under his
713@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@very eyes, with provoking insolence.
714@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“He began to speak as soon as he saw me. I had been very long on the road.  He
715@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@could not wait. Had to start without me. The up-river stations had to be
716@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@relieved. There had been so many delays already that he did not know who was
717@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@dead and who was alive, and how they got on—and so on, and so on. He paid no
718@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@attention to my explanations, and, playing with a stick of sealing-wax, repeated
719@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@several times that the situation was ’very grave, very grave.’ There were
720@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@rumours that a very important station was in jeopardy, and its chief, Mr. Kurtz,
721@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@was ill. Hoped it was not true. Mr.  Kurtz was... I felt weary and irritable.
722@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@Hang Kurtz, I thought.  I interrupted him by saying I had heard of Mr. Kurtz on
723@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@the coast. ‘Ah! So they talk of him down there,’ he murmured to himself. Then he
724@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@began again, assuring me Mr. Kurtz was the best agent he had, an exceptional
725@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@man, of the greatest importance to the Company; therefore I could understand his
726@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@anxiety. He was, he said, ‘very, very uneasy.’ Certainly he fidgeted on his
727@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@chair a good deal, exclaimed, ‘Ah, Mr. Kurtz!’ broke the stick of sealing-wax
728@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@and seemed dumfounded by the accident. Next thing he wanted to know ‘how long it
729@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@would take to’... I interrupted him again. Being hungry, you know, and kept on
730@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@my feet too. I was getting savage. ‘How can I tell?’ I said. ‘I haven’t even
731@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@seen the wreck yet—some months, no doubt.’ All this talk seemed to me so futile.
732@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@‘Some months,’ he said. ‘Well, let us say three months before we can make a
733@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@start. Yes. That ought to do the affair.’ I flung out of his hut (he lived all
734@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@alone in a clay hut with a sort of verandah) muttering to myself my opinion of
735@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@him. He was a chattering idiot.  Afterwards I took it back when it was borne in
736@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@upon me startlingly with what extreme nicety he had estimated the time requisite
737@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@for the ’affair.’
738@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“I went to work the next day, turning, so to speak, my back on that station. In
739@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@that way only it seemed to me I could keep my hold on the redeeming facts of
740@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@life. Still, one must look about sometimes; and then I saw this station, these
741@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@men strolling aimlessly about in the sunshine of the yard. I asked myself
742@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@sometimes what it all meant. They wandered here and there with their absurd long
743@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@staves in their hands, like a lot of faithless pilgrims bewitched inside a
744@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@rotten fence. The word ‘ivory’ rang in the air, was whispered, was sighed. You
745@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@would think they were praying to it. A taint of imbecile rapacity blew through
746@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@it all, like a whiff from some corpse. By Jove! I’ve never seen anything so
747@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@unreal in my life. And outside, the silent wilderness surrounding this cleared
748@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@speck on the earth struck me as something great and invincible, like evil or
749@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@truth, waiting patiently for the passing away of this fantastic invasion.
750@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“Oh, these months! Well, never mind. Various things happened. One evening a
751@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@grass shed full of calico, cotton prints, beads, and I don’t know what else,
752@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@burst into a blaze so suddenly that you would have thought the earth had opened
753@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@to let an avenging fire consume all that trash. I was smoking my pipe quietly by
754@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@my dismantled steamer, and saw them all cutting capers in the light, with their
755@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@arms lifted high, when the stout man with moustaches came tearing down to the
756@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@river, a tin pail in his hand, assured me that everybody was ‘behaving
757@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@splendidly, splendidly,’ dipped about a quart of water and tore back again. I
758@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@noticed there was a hole in the bottom of his pail.
759@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@“I strolled up. There was no hurry. You see the thing had gone off like a box of
760@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@matches. It had been hopeless from the very first. The flame had leaped high,
761@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@driven everybody back, lighted up everything—and collapsed.  The shed was
762@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@already a heap of embers glowing fiercely. A nigger was being beaten near by.
763@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@1@0@0@0@They said he had caused the fire in some way; be that as it may, he was
