1044@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@“One evening as I was lying flat on the deck of my steamboat, I heard voices
1045@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@approaching—and there were the nephew and the uncle strolling along the bank. I
1046@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@laid my head on my arm again, and had nearly lost myself in a doze, when
1047@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@somebody said in my ear, as it were: ‘I am as harmless as a little child, but I
1048@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@don’t like to be dictated to. Am I the manager—or am I not? I was ordered to
1049@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@send him there. It’s incredible.’ ... I became aware that the two were standing
1050@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@on the shore alongside the forepart of the steamboat, just below my head. I did
1051@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@not move; it did not occur to me to move: I was sleepy. ‘It _is_ unpleasant,’
1052@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@grunted the uncle. ‘He has asked the Administration to be sent there,’ said the
1053@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@other, ‘with the idea of showing what he could do; and I was instructed
1054@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@accordingly. Look at the influence that man must have. Is it not frightful?’
1055@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@They both agreed it was frightful, then made several bizarre remarks: ‘Make rain
1056@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@and fine weather—one man—the Council—by the nose’—bits of absurd sentences that
1057@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@got the better of my drowsiness, so that I had pretty near the whole of my wits
1058@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@about me when the uncle said, ‘The climate may do away with this difficulty for
1059@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@you. Is he alone there?’ ‘Yes,’ answered the manager; ‘he sent his assistant
1060@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@down the river with a note to me in these terms: ”Clear this poor devil out of
1061@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@the country, and don’t bother sending more of that sort. I had rather be alone
1062@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@than have the kind of men you can dispose of with me.“ It was more than a year
1063@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@ago. Can you imagine such impudence!’ ‘Anything since then?’ asked the other
1064@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@hoarsely. ‘Ivory,’ jerked the nephew; ‘lots of it—prime sort—lots—most annoying,
1065@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@from him.’ ‘And with that?’ questioned the heavy rumble. ‘Invoice,’ was the
1066@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@reply fired out, so to speak. Then silence. They had been talking about Kurtz.
1067@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@“I was broad awake by this time, but, lying perfectly at ease, remained still,
1068@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@having no inducement to change my position. ‘How did that ivory come all this
1069@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@way?’ growled the elder man, who seemed very vexed. The other explained that it
1070@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@had come with a fleet of canoes in charge of an English half-caste clerk Kurtz
1071@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@2@0@0@0@had with him; that Kurtz had apparently intended to return himself, the station
