2437@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@mould of primeval earth.  But both the diabolic love and the unearthly hate of
2438@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the mysteries it had penetrated fought for the possession of that soul satiated
2439@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@with primitive emotions, avid of lying fame, of sham distinction, of all the
2440@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@appearances of success and power.
2441@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“Sometimes he was contemptibly childish. He desired to have kings meet him at
2442@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@railway-stations on his return from some ghastly Nowhere, where he intended to
2443@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@accomplish great things. ‘You show them you have in you something that is really
2444@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@profitable, and then there will be no limits to the recognition of your
2445@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@ability,’ he would say. ‘Of course you must take care of the motives—right
2446@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@motives—always.’ The long reaches that were like one and the same reach,
2447@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@monotonous bends that were exactly alike, slipped past the steamer with their
2448@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@multitude of secular trees looking patiently after this grimy fragment of
2449@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@another world, the forerunner of change, of conquest, of trade, of massacres, of
2450@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@blessings. I looked ahead—piloting.  ‘Close the shutter,’ said Kurtz suddenly
2451@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@one day; ‘I can’t bear to look at this.’ I did so. There was a silence. ‘Oh, but
2452@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@I will wring your heart yet!’ he cried at the invisible wilderness.
2453@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“We broke down—as I had expected—and had to lie up for repairs at the head of an
2454@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@island. This delay was the first thing that shook Kurtz’s confidence.  One
2455@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@morning he gave me a packet of papers and a photograph—the lot tied together
2456@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@with a shoe-string. ‘Keep this for me,’ he said. ‘This noxious fool’ (meaning
2457@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the manager) ‘is capable of prying into my boxes when I am not looking.’ In the
2458@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@afternoon I saw him. He was lying on his back with closed eyes, and I withdrew
2459@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@quietly, but I heard him mutter, ‘Live rightly, die, die...’ I listened. There
2460@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@was nothing more. Was he rehearsing some speech in his sleep, or was it a
2461@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@fragment of a phrase from some newspaper article? He had been writing for the
2462@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@papers and meant to do so again, ‘for the furthering of my ideas. It’s a duty.’
2463@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“His was an impenetrable darkness. I looked at him as you peer down at a man who
2464@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@is lying at the bottom of a precipice where the sun never shines.  But I had not
2465@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@much time to give him, because I was helping the engine-driver to take to pieces
2466@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the leaky cylinders, to straighten a bent connecting-rod, and in other such
2467@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@matters. I lived in an infernal mess of rust, filings, nuts, bolts, spanners,
2468@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@hammers, ratchet-drills—things I abominate, because I don’t get on with them. I
2469@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@tended the little forge we fortunately had aboard; I toiled wearily in a
2470@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@wretched scrap-heap—unless I had the shakes too bad to stand.
2471@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“One evening coming in with a candle I was startled to hear him say a little
2472@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@tremulously, ‘I am lying here in the dark waiting for death.’ The light was
2473@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@within a foot of his eyes. I forced myself to murmur, ‘Oh, nonsense!’ and stood
2474@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@over him as if transfixed.
2475@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“Anything approaching the change that came over his features I have never seen
2476@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@before, and hope never to see again. Oh, I wasn’t touched. I was fascinated. It
2477@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@was as though a veil had been rent. I saw on that ivory face the expression of
2478@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@sombre pride, of ruthless power, of craven terror—of an intense and hopeless
2479@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@despair. Did he live his life again in every detail of desire, temptation, and
2480@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@surrender during that supreme moment of complete knowledge? He cried in a
2481@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@whisper at some image, at some vision—he cried out twice, a cry that was no more
2482@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@than a breath:
2483@sl>Single Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“‘The horror! The horror!’
2484@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“I blew the candle out and left the cabin. The pilgrims were dining in the
2485@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@mess-room, and I took my place opposite the manager, who lifted his eyes to give
2486@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@me a questioning glance, which I successfully ignored. He leaned back, serene,
2487@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@with that peculiar smile of his sealing the unexpressed depths of his meanness.
2488@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@A continuous shower of small flies streamed upon the lamp, upon the cloth, upon
2489@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@our hands and faces. Suddenly the manager’s boy put his insolent black head in
2490@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the doorway, and said in a tone of scathing contempt:
2491@sl>Single Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“‘Mistah Kurtz—he dead.’
2492@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“All the pilgrims rushed out to see. I remained, and went on with my dinner. I
2493@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@believe I was considered brutally callous. However, I did not eat much. There
2494@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@was a lamp in there—light, don’t you know—and outside it was so beastly, beastly
2495@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@dark. I went no more near the remarkable man who had pronounced a judgment upon
2496@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the adventures of his soul on this earth. The voice was gone. What else had been
2497@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@there? But I am of course aware that next day the pilgrims buried something in a
2498@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@muddy hole.
2499@sl>Single Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“And then they very nearly buried me.
2500@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“However, as you see, I did not go to join Kurtz there and then. I did not.  I
2501@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@remained to dream the nightmare out to the end, and to show my loyalty to Kurtz
2502@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@once more. Destiny. My destiny! Droll thing life is—that mysterious arrangement
2503@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@of merciless logic for a futile purpose. The most you can hope from it is some
2504@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@knowledge of yourself—that comes too late—a crop of unextinguishable regrets. I
2505@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@have wrestled with death. It is the most unexciting contest you can imagine. It
2506@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@takes place in an impalpable greyness, with nothing underfoot, with nothing
2507@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@around, without spectators, without clamour, without glory, without the great
2508@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@desire of victory, without the great fear of defeat, in a sickly atmosphere of
2509@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@tepid scepticism, without much belief in your own right, and still less in that
2510@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@of your adversary. If such is the form of ultimate wisdom, then life is a
2511@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@greater riddle than some of us think it to be. I was within a hair’s breadth of
2512@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the last opportunity for pronouncement, and I found with humiliation that
2513@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@probably I would have nothing to say. This is the reason why I affirm that Kurtz
2514@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@was a remarkable man. He had something to say. He said it. Since I had peeped
2515@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@over the edge myself, I understand better the meaning of his stare, that could
2516@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@not see the flame of the candle, but was wide enough to embrace the whole
2517@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@universe, piercing enough to penetrate all the hearts that beat in the darkness.
2518@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@He had summed up—he had judged. ‘The horror!’ He was a remarkable man. After
2519@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@all, this was the expression of some sort of belief; it had candour, it had
2520@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@conviction, it had a vibrating note of revolt in its whisper, it had the
2521@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@appalling face of a glimpsed truth—the strange commingling of desire and hate.
2522@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@And it is not my own extremity I remember best—a vision of greyness without form
2523@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@filled with physical pain, and a careless contempt for the evanescence of all
2524@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@things—even of this pain itself. No! It is his extremity that I seem to have
2525@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@lived through. True, he had made that last stride, he had stepped over the edge,
2526@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@while I had been permitted to draw back my hesitating foot. And perhaps in this
2527@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@is the whole difference; perhaps all the wisdom, and all truth, and all
2528@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@sincerity, are just compressed into that inappreciable moment of time in which
2529@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@we step over the threshold of the invisible.  Perhaps! I like to think my
2530@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@summing-up would not have been a word of careless contempt. Better his cry—much
2531@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@better. It was an affirmation, a moral victory paid for by innumerable defeats,
2532@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@by abominable terrors, by abominable satisfactions. But it was a victory! That
2533@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@is why I have remained loyal to Kurtz to the last, and even beyond, when a long
2534@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@time after I heard once more, not his own voice, but the echo of his magnificent
2535@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@eloquence thrown to me from a soul as translucently pure as a cliff of crystal.
2536@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“No, they did not bury me, though there is a period of time which I remember
2537@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@mistily, with a shuddering wonder, like a passage through some inconceivable
2538@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@world that had no hope in it and no desire. I found myself back in the
2539@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@sepulchral city resenting the sight of people hurrying through the streets to
2540@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@filch a little money from each other, to devour their infamous cookery, to gulp
2541@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@their unwholesome beer, to dream their insignificant and silly dreams. They
2542@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@trespassed upon my thoughts. They were intruders whose knowledge of life was to
2543@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@me an irritating pretence, because I felt so sure they could not possibly know
2544@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the things I knew. Their bearing, which was simply the bearing of commonplace
2545@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@individuals going about their business in the assurance of perfect safety, was
2546@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@offensive to me like the outrageous flauntings of folly in the face of a danger
2547@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@it is unable to comprehend. I had no particular desire to enlighten them, but I
2548@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@had some difficulty in restraining myself from laughing in their faces so full
2549@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@of stupid importance. I daresay I was not very well at that time.  I tottered
2550@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@about the streets—there were various affairs to settle—grinning bitterly at
2551@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@perfectly respectable persons. I admit my behaviour was inexcusable, but then my
2552@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@temperature was seldom normal in these days. My dear aunt’s endeavours to ‘nurse
2553@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@up my strength’ seemed altogether beside the mark. It was not my strength that
2554@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@wanted nursing, it was my imagination that wanted soothing. I kept the bundle of
2555@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@papers given me by Kurtz, not knowing exactly what to do with it. His mother had
2556@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@died lately, watched over, as I was told, by his Intended. A clean-shaved man,
2557@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@with an official manner and wearing gold-rimmed spectacles, called on me one day
2558@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@and made inquiries, at first circuitous, afterwards suavely pressing, about what
2559@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@he was pleased to denominate certain ‘documents.’ I was not surprised, because I
2560@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@had had two rows with the manager on the subject out there. I had refused to
2561@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@give up the smallest scrap out of that package, and I took the same attitude
2562@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@with the spectacled man. He became darkly menacing at last, and with much heat
2563@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@argued that the Company had the right to every bit of information about its
2564@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@‘territories.’ And said he, ‘Mr. Kurtz’s knowledge of unexplored regions must
2565@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@have been necessarily extensive and peculiar—owing to his great abilities and to
2566@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the deplorable circumstances in which he had been placed: therefore—’ I assured
2567@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@him Mr. Kurtz’s knowledge, however extensive, did not bear upon the problems of
2568@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@commerce or administration. He invoked then the name of science. ‘It would be an
2569@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@incalculable loss if,’ etc., etc. I offered him the report on the ‘Suppression
2570@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@of Savage Customs,’ with the postscriptum torn off. He took it up eagerly, but
2571@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@ended by sniffing at it with an air of contempt. ‘This is not what we had a
2572@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@right to expect,’ he remarked. ’Expect nothing else,’ I said. ‘There are only
2573@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@private letters.’ He withdrew upon some threat of legal proceedings, and I saw
2574@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@him no more; but another fellow, calling himself Kurtz’s cousin, appeared two
2575@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@days later, and was anxious to hear all the details about his dear relative’s
2576@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@last moments. Incidentally he gave me to understand that Kurtz had been
2577@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@essentially a great musician. ‘There was the making of an immense success,’ said
2578@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the man, who was an organist, I believe, with lank grey hair flowing over a
2579@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@greasy coat-collar. I had no reason to doubt his statement; and to this day I am
2580@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@unable to say what was Kurtz’s profession, whether he ever had any—which was the
2581@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@greatest of his talents. I had taken him for a painter who wrote for the papers,
2582@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@or else for a journalist who could paint—but even the cousin (who took snuff
2583@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@during the interview) could not tell me what he had been—exactly. He was a
2584@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@universal genius—on that point I agreed with the old chap, who thereupon blew
2585@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@his nose noisily into a large cotton handkerchief and withdrew in senile
2586@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@agitation, bearing off some family letters and memoranda without importance.
2587@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@Ultimately a journalist anxious to know something of the fate of his ‘dear
2588@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@colleague’ turned up. This visitor informed me Kurtz’s proper sphere ought to
2589@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@have been politics ‘on the popular side.’ He had furry straight eyebrows,
2590@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@bristly hair cropped short, an eyeglass on a broad ribbon, and, becoming
2591@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@expansive, confessed his opinion that Kurtz really couldn’t write a bit—‘but
2592@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@heavens! how that man could talk. He electrified large meetings.  He had
2593@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@faith—don’t you see?—he had the faith. He could get himself to believe
2594@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@anything—anything. He would have been a splendid leader of an extreme party.’
2595@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@‘What party?’ I asked. ‘Any party,’ answered the other. ‘He was
2596@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@an—an—extremist.’ Did I not think so? I assented. Did I know, he asked, with a
2597@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@sudden flash of curiosity, ‘what it was that had induced him to go out there?’
2598@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@‘Yes,’ said I, and forthwith handed him the famous Report for publication, if he
2599@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@thought fit. He glanced through it hurriedly, mumbling all the time, judged ‘it
2600@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@would do,’ and took himself off with this plunder.
2601@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“Thus I was left at last with a slim packet of letters and the girl’s portrait.
2602@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@She struck me as beautiful—I mean she had a beautiful expression.  I know that
2603@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@the sunlight can be made to lie, too, yet one felt that no manipulation of light
2604@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@and pose could have conveyed the delicate shade of truthfulness upon those
2605@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@features. She seemed ready to listen without mental reservation, without
2606@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@suspicion, without a thought for herself. I concluded I would go and give her
2607@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@back her portrait and those letters myself.  Curiosity? Yes; and also some other
2608@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@feeling perhaps. All that had been Kurtz’s had passed out of my hands: his soul,
2609@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@his body, his station, his plans, his ivory, his career. There remained only his
2610@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@memory and his Intended—and I wanted to give that up, too, to the past, in a
2611@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@way—to surrender personally all that remained of him with me to that oblivion
2612@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@which is the last word of our common fate. I don’t defend myself. I had no clear
2613@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@perception of what it was I really wanted. Perhaps it was an impulse of
2614@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@unconscious loyalty, or the fulfilment of one of those ironic necessities that
2615@ll>Last Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@lurk in the facts of human existence. I don’t know.  I can’t tell. But I went.
2616@fl>First Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@“I thought his memory was like the other memories of the dead that accumulate in
2617@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@every man’s life—a vague impress on the brain of shadows that had fallen on it
2618@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@in their swift and final passage; but before the high and ponderous door,
2619@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@between the tall houses of a street as still and decorous as a well-kept alley
2620@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@in a cemetery, I had a vision of him on the stretcher, opening his mouth
2621@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@voraciously, as if to devour all the earth with all its mankind. He lived then
2622@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@before me; he lived as much as he had ever lived—a shadow insatiable of splendid
2623@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@appearances, of frightful realities; a shadow darker than the shadow of the
2624@l>Line@nem>Line with No Emphasis@3@0@0@0@night, and draped nobly in the folds of a gorgeous eloquence. The vision seemed
